TextBlock.TextLine: In Antwerpen 16 July 1681
Aust John Button
mons.. Ick hebbe ul brief van 26 juni wel ontfangen dat ul in Colliers
wisselbrief accepteert, ende op sijns tuyt betaelt is wel, maer daer mede en kan
ick voort mijn geene betalinge doen: op 21 augusty ibso heeft ul geaccepteert
op Ies maenden waer van noch niet de helft en ben vol daen, sedert noch de geleven
frisaerden & kers & t boven dien op 16 aprill de in stucken sarges our in 3
maenden te betaelen, soo dat alles overstier & vervallen is, ick en hadde niet
getwijffelt ofte ick soude voor nu vol daen geweest hebben ende ul wet wel
hoe de engelsche gedurigh op mij treken soo dat ick het met kan gebeteren
maer ick ben genoet saekt ul oock te molesteren, ende tot betalinge versoeken
alsoo ick present opt ujtterste belast ben ende tot nae den oostniet
kan wachten, soo gelieft mij te seuvent geene mogelijk is: ick hebbe ul
balen mul verkocht tot ƒ5:- thoudert mits te laten verdinen met vernis
@ 16 ditto 1681
London Arthur Anneslay
me
Sr. in answer to yd of P. curitt have no news yett of thomas Elsdon from Eron
butt I hope so may arrive speedly I have examn the invoyce & pattarnes I could
have wished some draps cullours had been amonghst them as are amongh
the cloth serges butt now I hope mr. wood will be exaiter to compleat
the rest of the inclosed you have the sale oft 6 months for yd acctt of
which the proceedis ƒ3488:15 ½ are £581:9:3 flemish for which have
given you creditt sas also for yd ½ share in the 2 bales for our acctt
in comp. ƒ784:6½ £130:24:5: which in case you finde right please
to nate accordingly p. nest shall follow yd acctt. caritt, and am a
brasping monyes togheter to send with itt in hopes to cleare the
ine & the other to content whilst I subscribe my self -
@ 16 ditto
London Honry maynard
th
Sr. my last to you was on the 12: curitt sence non from you, so this
onelij for advise that thomas whito & John hasle wood are wele arived
for which thenkes be god, I hope the goods will prove to content, as alsoo
the packing press, for which have gven goods harge to mr. Coots: lett mee
know in answer how bayes are in the north for should incline to
in order a good parcell haveing sold our bale MN. 19: in closed acctt. of sale
of last month itt is now a dead time of the yeare not so much
in selling as scarecitie in mony which will be over suddamly, so that
theire Ill be the more forward in remises thought p. next shall follow
some without faile whilst I remaine with kinde saleeto

London John Loyd
Sr. I have before mee yd of P:. curitt & I am sorry that the drugett:
prove no better to content, the more, because I toock, so much care
about them, & used all the rethoricall words I could to make the maker
beleave to have great imploy & by those meanes to in corridge him to
provide an exceeding good tryall, in which I finde wee are frustrated
so hopes for the first or next a better. I observe what you witte concerning
three because you had reme, wee have had no less of late butt that is
onely good for all sort of winter goods, butt not for the summer
frints, as flox, rates, barly & the like which here is altoghete
doyed & spoiles & much more in silesia from whence wee have the
yeare of which tykes are made a freind of mne that sells that
com. in great quantities hath assured mee that itt is still rising thoug
itt is al ready deaver 20 Pic. then what itt ready was 4 a 5 monthe sence
the tykes lost is stivers a peece more then formely, & go much spayd
for them last markest, day in case you please any to that prijce
command feely & lett mee have yd order for nothwithstand ing
the rising have constant comissions from others I have butt fac now
by more mee & though I have engaged & good parcell yett the makers will not
deliver them makeing great complannts that they loose & so hano been
obligeed to allow them some thing more to have the orders complanted
for they will bj all apearence vise a guilder a peece a governo when you
command mee about nr norton yd ordre shall le don & soul
London Edmiand wannen
In Antwerp 16 July 1368
th
Sr. I have before mee yd aggreable of 28: past. which come with the letters
rinio
of p. curies the mentioned packest is att colonia and as i supose on itts way
hether for, before I had yd have given the nessecary order how to send itt
forward because I knew how those packetts are expediated & that itt not should
be detained, I exspect to have itt here in aday or 2 & then shall send itt to m.
valego to newport, to dispatch itt by the next packett bout to Dover, where
mr. Willsam Eaton is the ordinary man for that trade, & mr. vallego his
heef correspondent, yett shall write him to follow yd order you may
order what you please, & command mee where in you iiudge my service
capable & I shall endeavour to be exact in complyance. I shall also provide
a small packest of flanders laces in which I do not question butt you will
finde contente for I know what is most demanded in England con
haveing constantdirection to that purpose, wee make use of no other war
then by way of newporte & Dover thought somes times I did send packetts
bij long so gea from ostend which did also come safe to hand for
wee have dayly vessels there for london which easely know how to rem
some such small cargoes what you shall order mee shall be performede
@ 16 ditto
Dublin Elnathan Lumin
Sr. I have recd. 2 of yd of 28 & 21 past. by which I understand yd desire to provide
some laces which shall be don accordingly, with all imaguiable care, exact
to yd order for I make itt myc bussines to buy that com. - I hope you recd
the guild leather & tapstrey hanging long before now & that they gave
content, of which should be glad to heare, as also to know if this comes
to yd hand for least yeare wrott severall letters to you & never heare from
yotu, so that I feared they were miscarried where in I can serve you
freely command mee & if I meet with any boddy, thatwant as
correspondent att Dublin I shall not faile to promote yd intrest whilst I a
london Henry Collier
th

@ 16 ditto
Sr. in answer to yd of 24 past & S. curitt as to the concernes of TH wee
doubt not butt wee shall prevaile thought the great vacantie begon last
saturday & then his procuror said that he woulld satisfye before that should
besuded itt yett wee forind good not to delay butt by letters from the court
of brussels to proceed which shall be performed & not leave him attrest, till
one or other: I take not ice of yd old proposition & excuse of Drawing
trualy you are not sensible how searey mony is with us here & I am
not for redrawing neither & yett not you continew up on mee as if
all what I sell were for ready mony, there by you know that goods you
sended this yeare, so all things ought to be some what proporitionably
because I would fame please others to I chanck you foryd
re commandation to mr. wanner I shall do all I can to serve him
punctually to content of the 6 cloathes I sent buck to you mine was
N. 9 a 26¾ yd oost 12:6, pray att lett mee know the proceed to note all
in conformitie &y on will oblige
@ 16 ditto 1681
Brugge Raphael Coots
mijn Hr sedert den mijnen van 14 deser, Beijde de ul van 13 & 14 ditto ontfangen
het pack N. 20 is mij prompt geworden, daer voren ul perticulierlijk hebte
bedancken: N. 22 waghte adroiture beneffens de 2 packen aen boort stephen wanner
& hasle wood daer bij oock de pack perse die ander mael ont hooghst ul gerecommand
blijve wille niet twijffelen, ofte van costij een beurtschip herrewaerts sal
gelnden worden mits nu drij schepen samen gearriveert sijn &light waght
genoch voor een adroiture herrewaerts maer icken kan niet genogh
verwonderen waer omgedocht wort soo om bequane & niet de nghde scheppen
gemployeert worden als nu onlangh hier sijn gekomen nae demael costij
cloeke bij landers genoch sijn wat passeirt verneme geirne & naeraet
Brussel Seger vanderborght
